SIMPLE: sensibility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sensibility
<hw>Sen`si*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Sensibilities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>sensibilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, LL. <ets>sensibilitas</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The quality or state of being
sensible, or capable of sensation; capacity to feel or
perceive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The capacity of emotion or feeling, as distinguished
from the intellect and the will; peculiar susceptibility of impression,
pleasurable or painful; delicacy of feeling; quick emotion or sympathy;
<as>as, <ex>sensibility</ex> to pleasure or pain; <ex>sensibility</ex>
to shame or praise; exquisite <ex>sensibility</ex></as>; -- often used
in the plural.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sensibilities</xex> so fine!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The true lawgiver ought to have a heart full of
<qex>sensibility</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>sensibilities</qex> seem rather to have been those of
patriotism than of wounded pride.</q> <rj><qau>Marshall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Experience of sensation; actual feeling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This adds greatly to my <qex>sensibility</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That quality of an instrument which makes it
indicate very slight changes of condition; delicacy; <as>as, the
<ex>sensibility</ex> of a balance, or of a thermometer</as>.</def><--
usu. sensitivity -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Taste; susceptibility; feeling. See
<er>Taste</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sensible</ent>⟦br⟧
